118. Pascal's Triangle
Given an integer numRows, return the first numRows of Pascal's triangle.
In Pascal's triangle, each number is the sum of the two numbers directly above it as shown:


Example 1:
Input: numRows = 5
Output: [[1],[1,1],[1,2,1],[1,3,3,1],[1,4,6,4,1]]

Example 2:
Input: numRows = 1
Output: [[1]]
 

Constraints:
1 <= numRows <= 30

###We have used nCr combination formula to find single element of Pascal Traingle if row and col is given i.e n=row and r=col 
while calculating take row-1 C col-1

###We have used res*(n-i) and res=res/i formula to print the entire row of pascal.
  //Entire nth row of the Pascal triangle
   public static void printNthRow(int n){
    double res=1;
     System.out.print(res+" ");
    for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
      res= res*(n-i);
      res=res/(i);
      System.out.print(res+" ");
    }
  }

### By using the above method we can print the whole triangle if we run loop from 1 to N
Solution:-

class Solution {
    public List<Integer> generateRow(int row){
    List<Integer> ansRow=new ArrayList<Integer>();
    int ans=1;
    ansRow.add(1);
    
    for(int col=1;col<row;col++){
      ans= ans*(row-col);
      ans=ans/col;
      ansRow.add(ans);
      //System.out.print(res+" ");
    }
    return ansRow;
    }
    public List<List<Integer>> generate(int numRows) {
        List<List<Integer>> ans= new ArrayList<List<Integer>>();
        //ans.add(new List<Integer>());
        for(int i=1;i<=numRows;i++){
            ans.add(generateRow(i));
        }
        return ans;
    }
}
